sec.p:
            PotamolepisMarshall, 1883
(
Potamolepidae
) is an endemic Afrotropical genus (
Manconi & Pronzato 2002
; 
Manconi & Pronzato 2009
) comprising of seven valid species (see 

Van Soest 
et al
. 2019

): 
P. leubnitziaeMarshall, 1883
; 
P. chartariaMarshall, 1883
; 
P. pechueliMarshall, 1883
; 
P. weltneriMoore, 1903
; 
P. marshalliBurton, 1938
; 
P. microporaBurton, 1938
and 
P. belinganaLevi, 1965
and has never been recorded from any other terrestrial realm (
Manconi & Pronzato 2002
; 
2009
; Manconi 
et al
. 2015).

Freshwater specimens were collected from Brazil and South Africa (
). The specimens from Brazil were collected Xingu River ( 3.560917° S ; 52.28524° W ), Amazônica Basin Altamira municipality. The specimen from South Africa was collected from Lake Bhangazi-North ( 27.65397° S , 32.61852° E ), a large freshwater endorheic coastal lake 20 km south of Sodwana Bay, KwaZulu-Natal , South Africa . Samples were preserved in 70% ethanol. Spicule slides and Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM) spicule preparations were made following
Hajdu et al . (2011)
. Clean spicules for SEM examination were spread on a plastic disc, air-dried, and coated with gold palladium for 20 minutes. Spicules were viewed on a Quanta 200 FEG Scanning Electron Microscope. Spicule dimensions are given as the mean length (range) × mean width (range) of 30 spicule measurements (minimum-mean-maximum length/width). Gross morphology, spicules and skeletal organization were carefully observed in all specimens for comparison purposes to non-gemmule freshwater sponges available in the World Porifera Database (
van Soest et al. 2019
).

tp:treatment-sec.p:
(

; 
Table 1
)

Skeleton.
Ectosomal skeleton not observed. Choanosomal skeleton is an anisotropic paucispicular reticulation. Spongin scarce (

).

Spicules. Megascleres.
Strongyles, smooth, straight to slightly curved, mucronated, 261–332.2–386 / 19–25– 29 μm (

). 
Microscleres
. Oxeas, smooth, straight, 138–161.5–200 / 6–7.1–10 μm (

). Gemmules and gemmuloscleres absent (
Table 1
).

Diagnosis. Sponge forming initial minute whitish tufts at the base of other sponges. Consistency firm. Skeleton a renieroid reticulation with scanty spongin cementing the extremities of the megascleres together at the reticular nodes. Megascleres in two categories. Primary megascleres thick, curved to straight acanthotylostrongyles, the curved ones with the concave section of the spicule smooth and the outer one spined. The spines grouped in small spots or forming half rings on the convex section of the spicule, the tylote extremities entirely covered with minute spines. Secondary megascleres slim, straight to slightly curved anisostrongyles presenting several irregularly distributed microspined tubercules along the spicule length except at the extremities, which are invariably covered with minute spines. Microscleres unknown or absent. Gemmules unknown. Adult sponge also unknown (
Volkmer-Ribeiro et al . 2009
).

